eper into the Styx's world, definitely get it."
76561198041725120,Recommended,216910,9234703,"Posted: 23 February, 2014",all,Auberon,"One of the best and original games I´ve played in  a long while. The story was captivating, the music gave me chills, the combat, well, I would describe it as the thinking mans dragon age. It obviously had flaws, the biggest was that there was too little of everything. I finished it in about 13 hours and am left dreaming of a sequel.I noticed this game just around the time it came out, but  waited with a buy until it was discounted and sat on it for even longer as I had read so much negative feedback beforehand. I wish I could go back in time, buy it at release to support the studio, and get on the barricades to defend it against all the flaming. I can understand a lot of the critisicm, however I think it all boils down to this game being unaccessable to a lot of people due to the challenge of the combat system, and the game being marketed in a way that perhaps fooled people it was a more action-oriented game with a bigger budget. The trailer kind of looked like gears of war with orcs, to be honest.I could write a lot about this game but will just summarize the main points;I enjoyed the combat, allthough a little unforgiving at some points, it did let me think up different tactics for different battles. The skills were fun and there were a few easier patches that let you feel powerful. Gear managment was a little thin but worked okay. Leveling your characters was business as usual with stat and skill points, with some new intresting bits such as deflection and stability. The game looks and plays beautifully. Encountered only a few minor glitches (perhaps it has been patched a bit?). Voice acting quality varied throughout the game from excellent (main characters) to crappy, but I only disliked a few of the actors.The bad? ""Corridor running"" which I did not really mind, as I enjoyed the combat and the quests.Slow paced combat, so be prepared if you don´t like that sort of thing. Lack of in-game cinematics or at least more cinematic finishes to some of the more epic events, which left some anti-climatic feelings at parts. And in the end, a lack of budget? If there would have been some more time and resources to flesh more stuff out, this could have been a dragon age killing tripple A.I can´t help but picturing a sequel of magnitude, with deeper tactical combat, different character choices, a more open world with continuation of the story.If you enjoy tactical RPG´s - a must play, if you came here looking for an action game, you should probably head back.As for me?  Would marry/10."
,Recommended,216910,15166194,"Posted: 2 April, 2015",all,Koko Sabre *Scruffy*,"Dont you ever get sick of the hate towards orcs and goblins? Being always the evil force in games? Well dont know about you but I do,thats for sure. And OOAM let me kill humans now... how refreshing .Story,Quests and LevelsYou are Arkail,fearsome orc,who is apointed with the assassination of the Emperor. In your journey you will be lead by Styx,master of stealth and assassination. Story is linear with here and there some decision making. At 2-3 points you will end up in hub-like area from which you can get different side quests to complete and improve yourself. The levels you will find are linear,each of them separated in ""zones"" .  There isnt much of exploration which can be bad or good depending on the player.RPG elementsWell you can equip your characters with some items and pick skills everytime they level up. Later in the game you are given 2 options per character to specialize them. Nothing to deep. Its simple but its doing its job in the game.CombatCombat is in 2 phases(or if you are good enough you can pick just one of them):1st. Stealth: you put Arkail in some spots save and use Styx to wonder around and kill guards without being seen. It takes time but make Phase 2 much easier... talking about phase 2.2.Once detected every guard from the ""zone"" will charge at you and fun time starts. Combat is action-based,there isnt pause button to set a lineup of skills for the orc and goblin to use. Instead you are given slow-motion button so you have to be fast with selecting targets and skills.  Combat needs sometime to get used to it. One thing that you should have in mind, Arkail got a berserk stance, while he do and takes dmg berserk fills and once full he goes all nuts,take less dmg,deals more dmg and attacks everything that moves... even Styx so run for the hills if this happens.ReplayabilityOnly reason to replay the game is to pick different decisions at places but for most people even one playthrough will be good enough.OverallA nice and solid RPG with interesting combat and story to tell."
76561198012626337,Recommended,216910,31765555,Posted: 15 May,all,Hellios Rayearth,"An obscure and underrated game that deserves a chance from curious gamers.Rating(s):Visuals & Graphics:7/10The game was not bad to the eyes by any means, but it wasn’t wasn’t great either. I understand that they were trying to use a more cartoony design that’s close to the Warcraft feel but something about it just felt off. Majority of the storyline is spent in dark, dreary locations and even when you are in open spaces the environment is either set at night, raining or just shaded heavy grey by dark clouds. I know that the game is infiltration-themed, but a variety of settings could’ve been easy on the eyes. Given that the game difficult, continuously repeating large segments of the game will eventually get to you.  Visual appeal is important, it’s one of the ways gamers get through the frustration of working with a difficult game. It was painful for me to marathon through this. Could’ve been much betterMusic and Sound:10/10One of the best I have heard in awhile. The only way I was able to marathon through this game was put the OST on youtube and had my favorite battle themes on repeat. It get’s your blood going. Amazing work. The orchestral parts were done well. Being a cello player myself, the score used in the tracks were amazing. I’m actually trying to blind-play it at the moment. Wish I can get hold of the official score.Plot/Story:9/10Very strong. Main characters had distinct lovable personalities. Flow of the plot was smooth and coherent. It’s a cliche plot and some parts were predictable but nevertheless it was nice to watch through it.Gameplay and Mechanics:6/10Most of the reviews will tell you that the game mechanics suck, and for the most part I understand why they say that it is. The game is very reminiscent of Dragon Age (1). It uses a real time strategy combat system that you can pause and interrupt to issue more “complex” actions. You literally micromanage your team’s position every step of the way so that you can better tackle every encounter. Given that the game is very challenging on Extreme. You really do have to get familiar with gameplay.So where does this game go wrong? Well, in Dragon Age, you can pause mid-fight and use your mouse to reposition your character in the battle field, having complete control and awareness of your full team location. Enabling you to manage agro, employ better kiting, making use of choke points for better tanking, etc;In Of Orcs and Men, the strategical play behaves a lot like a game console. Instead of using your mouse to direct your team’s position you basically move them in real-time. The consequence of that is you lose sight of your other character’s position only leaving you to decide by looking at his life bar. I’m not sure if the design was intentional or if it was because this game was originally for consoles and was just later ported to PC, but the general feel of the gameplay is clunky and unnatural. The game does not make use of the capabilities of a PC, and as a result, majority of the difficulty in playing the game stems from this. Personally, I could have finished Extreme, 4-5 hours less the time it took me if the controls worked similarly to DA.Conclusion:Barely makes the cut. Of Orcs and Men is like how F13 is to me. Hate the gameplay, but love it for its story and characters. If you are a “story-guy” like me, I highly recommend the game for you."
76561198026221093,Recommended,216910,7850291,"Posted: 30 November, 2013",all,FireBrand,"Surprisingly entertaining playing from an orc perspective,  as the story is probably it's strongest point. The gameplay is more tactical then anything, and requires you to invest in talents so the 2 characters compliment each other to maximum efficiency.  Definitely no regrets buying this discounted."
,Recommended,216910,27012531,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Cousin Okri,"Writing this review a long time after actually playing the game, but here goes. The game had♥♥♥♥♥♥poor marketing, so I feel it my duty to give it a voice, however small.It's a flawed little gem of grim-bright fantasy that explores some interesting concepts that you'll find most RPG's don't play with like:A soundtrack that isn't identical to LoTR (and is trully one of a kind)A dialog system that allows you to control both party members and who talks in an encounter-(God I wish there was another RPG that let this happen)A story told from the perspective of ""the bad guys"", the Orcs!-the characters are good, some are more unique than others-The setting looks high fantasy but it has some pretty grim dialogue/story (slavery, genocide, racism)--Magic in this setting is more subtle (akin to Gandalf in LoTR, rather than your avg WoW fireball slinging-mage) which has its own charmA combat system that has unique features and doesn't feel canned-the mechanics behind your main brawler is HILARIOUS, he can go ape♥♥♥♥♥♥crazy and start to pick ♥♥♥♥ers up and breaking their spine. Including your goblin buddy! (This mechanic actually makes the combat refreshing, the loss of control isn't bad if you just know how to use it to your advantage.)-You'll feel massive changes when fighting heavily armored knights vs your average guardSo what are the flaws?The game has a short run-time, for an RPG. You can blast through it fairly quick and feel satisfied.The combat system has quite a bit of jargon, sometimes you'll resort to just queueing up attacks and hope for the best-Eventually you master it and it becomes pretty easyThe gear choices are sparse, and often won't feel like they make significant changes to your characterThe stealth is ham handed and is much less satisfying than the combat. The branch-off to this game (Styx: Master of Shadows) does the stealth much better.Its likely going to be priced very low so you should give it a chance. Trust me, there's things to love in the game."
