,Recommended,216910,31659232,Posted: 9 May,all,Aurumlamina,"Every once in awhile I give a game the benefit of the doubt and give it a go even if I'm on the fence over whether it appears to be worth my time or not.  Often, my gut feeling is correct and the game turns out to be a mediocre experience at best.  However, Of Orcs and Men is one of the exceptions and ended up being a great game.Of Orcs and Men has one of the best narrative experiences that I've played in a linear RPG.  You play through the tale of a Bloodjaw, an elite orcish warrior, who is on a mission to kill the human emperor who has been eradicating and enslaving his people.  The reversal of roles very much helps push the narrative as you see it from the eyes of an orc, instead of the humans, elves, and dwarves that are against him.  Shortly after leaving for his quest, the orc is approached by a goblin with a completely lack of morals who acts as the personality counterbalance to the honorable and straightforward orc that the game begins with.  The adventure that follows is full of twists and turns that will keep you on the edge of your seat as you are absorbed into the atmosphere of the world,The combat mechanics of the game are not anywhere near as impressive as the narrative, though I found them to be adequate.  You control both the orc (Arkail) and the goblin (Styx) in a real-time with pause combat system that reminds me of Dragon Age to an extent.  Character building was entertaining as there are a number of ways to build your characters so that they perform like a well-oiled machine.  There are several stats and two skills trees that are unique to the characters, and both of these mechanics are there for you to customize your playstyle.  An additional perk to add to the mix is that at a cerain part in the story each of your characters makes a choice regarding their own story arc that upgrades them to one of two classes narratively tied to it.Of Orcs and Men is a game that you should get to playing right away if you are a fan of games with a good narrative and can let yourself be pulled into the world.  If you are a heavily mechanical player, you may not enjoy this title as much but I would still recommend giving it a chance as I found the game in its entirety to be a memorable experience.  Overall, Of Orcs and Men is a solid entry into the RPG genre and one that I am very happy that I gave a chance even if I am several years late."
