76561197971872842,Not Recommended,216910,17113071,"Posted: 18 July, 2015",all,Riph,"Of Orcs and Men is, at its core, a tactical RPG about the interesting symbiosis between a rogue and a warrior in a fantasy RPG.  The warrior has a stun attack with a high chance of being dodged.  The rogue has an attack which prevents the target from dodging for 5 seconds.  Put them together and you feel clever!  This gameplay works, and we've seen it work in other games.  For example, the original Dragon Age had the exact same symbiosis between a rogue and a warrior and it worked great there.  However....This is a negative review, but I'll start with the good:+ Very glad to see some variety in story.  The greenskins as protagonists is an interesting angle.  The story itself is mostly good.+ Graphics are decent.+ Combat has enough depth to be interesting, with lots of abilities which synnergize with each other to produce new effects.The bad:- The voice actors sound like they're muddling through lines in a second language.  Worse, it sounds like several of the lines are translated literally from the original french, meaning clever local idioms just become nonsense.- Game was obviously written solely with an xbox controller in mind.  When you reach a hill and have to move your mouse back to look 'up', you have to pull it about three mousepadlengths because the Y coordinate has a different sensativity than the X coordinate.  This cannot be changed in the options.-Combat is a miserable, stumbling affair.  This is the killer.  If you're skimming, read this part.As I mentioned above, the whole game is about doing clever things with your rogue and warrior TOGETHER.  So you'd assume that, generally, they target the same enemy, right?  Wrong.  Their autotargetting ALWAYS chooses different enemies, so I'm being totally serious when I say 50% of my game time was simply smashing the Q and E keys paging through interminable lists of targets trying to get them to both hit the same guy.  This would be less of a problem if the click selection works, but it doesn't.  The camera is locked 2 feet from the action, usually staring at a wall, and clicking an enemy is just as likely to select the guy 20 meters behind him as it is to select him.This is a game about combat in which I like everything except the combat.  The combat is awful.  Can not recommend."
