,Not Recommended,216910,21697730,"Posted: 7 March, 2016",all,Tardivex,"Of Orcs and Men is a game with some interesting ideas but ultimatly fails in a whole lot more areas than it actually succeeds, which seems to be a common theme with this developer as I'm playing through their games... Anyways let's get to it shall we?CombatI've had to rewrite this section actually because originally I had a big rant about the combat here but it took way too many characters and didn't leave much room for the other stuff in this review, you can stillread it if you're interested though, anyways here's the short and to the point versionThe combat is pretty bad, and playing on harder difficulties only makes it worse, you control 2 characters, a big warrior orc and a small rogue goblin, they both have unique abilites that you select from a weird wheel which slows time when it pops up as you press the space key, suffice to say it's quite clunky because the game doesn't know if it wants to be turn based or real time and it's just this really weird ""strategic"" combat as a resultIt's a very clunky system that feels unpolished, you can't dodge / block damage in a straightforward way, it's all up to some stats and RNG, same for your enemies blocking / countering / dodging and the stupid rage mechanic for your big orc character (I go into more detail about that on the longer version) and you're always overwhelmed in numbers which limit a lot your options since only a few skills can be upgraded to be uninterruptable because the enemies interrupt most of your other attacks by hitting youA lot of encounters devolved into me using the goblin character running around in circles to avoid enemies to revive the big orc, getting 1-2 hits with him, dying and getting revived again over and over again until everyone was dead, sometimes they got hits on the goblin aswell and if he died it got even worse by the two characters reviving each other all the time and barely getting any hits in to kill the enemies, but you have to play as only 1 character in some sections which can make things even more frustratingYou can also use stealth to 1 hit K.O dudes with your goblin before you get spotted and it's a very useful way of thinning the enemies ranks before you inevitably have to face them in ""real"" combat, but there are a lot of fights triggered by cutscenes or with enemy placement which you can't stealth your way out of so there's thatExplorationSo yeah, safe to say I'm not really happy with the combat at all, it's pure ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t a lot of times and I haven't been frustrated like this with a game in a long time, the real kicker is that you know what you do for like 90% of the whole game? Just go through straight corridors walking very slowly as a big fat orc (or a small goblin) until you get into slightly bigger rooms with a bunch of dudes in them, kill them all, go through another corridor, get to another slightly bigger room, rinse and repeat until you get to the objective at the end of the map, for the whole game, it seriously takes its toll upon you and the first time I played this game was for around 1-2 hours, but I really thought I've been playing for the whole day, serisouly it felt like an eternity, this game's combat really grinds upon your very soul and the only real exploration is that there's maybe a slightly shorter branching corridor which leads to another big room with lots of dudes in it and some loot, or you get a sidequest from an NPC in one of the hub areas and you go through the exact same formula of going through corridors and then big rooms againStoryThe story while it may seem interesting at times, but it's pretty meh, there's nothing really all that special about it, I think the main thing here is that it's different in a way not many other games explore because you play as Orcs and Goblins which usually are the evil bad guys and all that, but yeah this time around the humans are evil and conquered almost all the orcs and enslaved them, you're in control of an orc named Arkail, a strong elite warrior which is part of the Bloodjaws clan on a crazy suicide mission to kill the human emperor and hopefully make things better for his kin, and also Styx, a goblin rogue type character helping him along the wayThe voice acting is a mixed bag as usual with this developer and the same can be said about the characters, some can be pretty likeable like Styx which is probably one of the reasons he's got his own game which maybe I'll try at some point and then there are your generic villains or the twist which you could see from a mile away near the endBut ultimatly the story is just that, it has a nice / different coat of paint with it's setting, I'll have to admit that's what kept me going but it's pretty average and I didn't feel any real sense of satisfaction after completing it (aside from being free from the horrifying combat maybe) and at no point I really felt invested or cared for any of the characters, the only real fun one is Styx to be quite honest, the others vary on the spectrum from fine to stereotypical trope ""x"" or ""y"" characterYou have some choices but few actually matter, a lot of it it the same whatever you choose with some differences only being like a line of dialogue, the bigger changes / minor consequences are a result of sidequests if you wish to go for thoseConclusionAll in all I'd have to say that while it's different it's a pretty mediocre game, you're doing the same thing for pretty much all of it i.e the ""Exploration"" section from this review and sadly that same thing is just not all that fun to do, maybe the story might intrigue you in some way but I wouldn't hold by breath on it, it's sad to say this because this game did have some cool potential but it just didn't come to fruition, honestly don't bother with this one, but if you REALLY want to give it a go for whatever reason at least do yoruself a favor and wait to pick it up on sale"
