,Recommended,216910,21856847,"Posted: 15 March, 2016",all,dj_moyer,"Eh, it's ok.  Not great, but maybe see if you can get it on sale for cheap.This is an adventure RPG.  You follow a linear set path, deal with enemies a few at a time, find some hidden treasures, change and upgrade your armor and weapons, and gain experience points from combat to level up your skills.  The world is a ""fantasy"" setting where the humans have come together and formed an empire after a long war against the Orcs.  Now the emperor is running a campaign of genocide against anything with green skin.  The dwarves and elves have joined him, mostly out of fear for their own people.In this game, you play as two characters.  You can switch control from one to the other on the fly, but whichever one you are NOT controlling will be active with AI control.  The AI is stupid as a bag of rocks, by the way.  The big orc is loud and likes to hit people in the face.  He has a mission:  to save his species from genocide by assassinating the human emperor.  The little goblin is tasked with helping the orc get through the city so he can do the deed.  The little goblin is very sneaky; if he enters stealth mode then the big guy will stop following you and wait until you exit stealth mode before he runs to catch up.  While in stealth mode, many times you can make a fight easier - or avoid a fight completely - by sneaking behind the enemy and assassinating them one at a time.  If a fight does break out because you are witnessed killing a soldier, then you will be alternating control between the two.  You can set a chain of commands for each of them, but they can only remember four commands at once.  Each character has his own upgrade tree, for which you gain points when you level-up.  There is one area that has SHARED commands for both of them, and each character has two fighting styles to upgrade.  The goblin has a path for ranged attacks (dagger toss) and another path for up-close fighting.  The orc has a path for strong but slow attacks, and another for attacks that allow him to also block or parry incoming blows.The graphics are pretty well done.  The music isn't awful, but also not great.  The story is interesting because it is rare that you get to play as a ""bad guy"" but still have it feel like you're doing the right thing.  The combat, in my opinion, is pretty terrible though.  And the path you are allowed to follow is extremely limited.  That does detract from the fun story aspects a bit, so I only give this one a rating of ""Eh, it's ok"" whereas if the combat system had been done a little better I might actually call it a good game.Story:  good stuff.Combat:  terrible, though the stealth assassination style is amusing for a little while.Still worth playing?  Sure, if you can get it for just a few bucks.  Don't shell out big money for this one though.If you try this one and enjoy it, consider another game in the series:  ""Styx: Master of Shadows"" which as of writing this I still have not played."
